  "statusCode": 200,
  "body": "{\"query\":\"12 factor app configuration logs disposability backing services official\",\"follow_up_questions\":null,\"answer\":null,\"images\":[],\"results\":[{\"url\":\"https://www.libelle.com/blog/twelve-factor-app-codebase-dependencies-config-backing-services\",\"title\":\"Libelle IT Blog: The Twelve Factor App Part 1: Codebase, Dependencies, Config Backing Services | Libelle IT Group\",\"content\":\"* The Twelve Factor App Part 1: Codebase, Dependencies, Config Backing Services. The 12-factor app represents a methodology of creating Software-as-a-service (SAAS) app. The twelve-factor methodology can be applied to apps written in any programming language, and which use any combination of backing services (database, queue, memory cache, etc). A 12-factor app is always tracked in a version control system, stated as: “One codebase tracked in revision control, many deploys.” (Source). In this factor, multiple codebases and multiple apps with shared the same code, breaks the twelve-factor methodology, and each of them have a solution to avoid this scenario. There is only one codebase per app, but there will be many deploys of the app. A deploy is a running instance of the app. Internal information that is part of the app must not be included in the  configuration. Each backing service is considered as a resource which may be integrated to and excluded from deploys at a certain moment.\",\"score\":0.643173,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://www.12factor.net\",\"title\":\"The Twelve-Factor App\",\"content\":\"# The Twelve-Factor App. In the modern era, software is commonly delivered as a service: called *web apps*, or *software-as-a-service*. The twelve-factor app is a methodology for building software-as-a-service apps that:. The twelve-factor methodology can be applied to apps written in any programming language, and which use any combination of backing services (database, queue, memory cache, etc). The contributors to this document have been directly involved in the development and deployment of hundreds of apps, and indirectly witnessed the development, operation, and scaling of hundreds of thousands of apps via our work on the Heroku platform. This document synthesizes all of our experience and observations on a wide variety of software-as-a-service apps in the wild. It is a triangulation on ideal practices for app development, paying particular attention to the dynamics of the organic growth of an app over time, the dynamics of collaboration between developers working on the app’s codebase, and avoiding the cost of software erosion.\",\"score\":0.44622982,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://www.redhat.com/en/blog/12-factor-app\",\"title\":\"An illustrated guide to 12 Factor Apps\",\"content\":\"Simplify the way you build, deploy, and manage apps. Learn how to use our cloud products and solutions at your own pace in the Red Hat® Hybrid Cloud Console. Discover resources and tools to help you build, deliver, and manage cloud-native applications and services. The 12 Factor App is a set of principles that describes a way of making software that, when followed, enables companies to create code that can be released reliably, scaled quickly, and maintained in a consistent and predictable manner. The **Codebase** principle states that all assets related to an application, everything from source code, the provisioning script, and configuration settings, are stored in a source code repository that is accessible to development, testing, and system administration staff. The principle of **Dependencies** asserts that only code that is unique and relevant to the purpose of the application is stored in source control. For example, you can have one set of configuration settings for a deployment intended for a testing environment and a different set for a deployment designed for a production environment.\",\"score\":0.40797067,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://developer.ibm.com/articles/creating-a-12-factor-application-with-open-liberty\",\"title\":\"Creating cloud-native applications: 12-factor applications\",\"content\":\"The binding of an application to its backing services should be done via external configuration. It should be possible to attach and detach backing services\",\"score\":0.3941782,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://zachcolinwolpe.medium.com/the-twelve-factor-app-83a9e4fc7afc\",\"title\":\"The Twelve-Factor App. This post summarises the methodology…\",\"content\":\"A twelve-factor app manages each config independently for each deploy. This scales smoothly as the app naturally expands into more deploys. IV.\",\"score\":0.23784177,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://oneuptime.com/blog/post/2026-02-20-twelve-factor-app-guide/view\",\"title\":\"Understanding the Twelve-Factor App Methodology\",\"content\":\"Catalog every service you run. Open Source — Self-host or use our cloud. Everything you need to get started and succeed. # Understanding the Twelve-Factor App Methodology. A practical guide to the twelve-factor app methodology for building cloud-native applications that scale reliably. The twelve-factor app methodology is a set of principles for building software-as-a-service applications. A[Twelve-Factor App] --> B[I. A twelve-factor app has exactly one codebase tracked in version control, with many deploys. A deploy is a running instance of the app - production, staging, or a developer's local environment. If you have multiple codebases, it is not an app - it is a distributed system. Each component in a distributed system should itself be a twelve-factor app. Declare all dependencies explicitly in a manifest file and use an isolation tool to ensure no implicit dependencies leak in. # The app does not know or care which environment it is in. A twelve-factor app makes no distinction between local and third-party services.\",\"score\":0.19962023,\"raw_content\":null}],\"response_time\":0.94,\"request_id\":\"70f7f7d9-8e06-4826-855a-a4edb880fa95\"}"
